	<h2>Ranking System</h2>
	<p class = "left_align"> We rank players using the <a href="http://trueskill.org/">Python implementation</a> of the <a href="https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/research/project/trueskill-ranking-system/">Microsoft Trueskill</a> ranking algorithm. Trueskill only takes set wins and losses into account; game counts are not used in the ranking formula but are archived on our site as interesting data. Our system currently supports processing finished brackets from <a href="https://help.smash.gg/hc/en-us/articles/217471947-API-Access">SmashGG</a> and <a href="https://api.challonge.com/v1">Challonge.</a></p>

	<p class = "left_align"> The numbers on your 
	<a href="{{url_for('player',player_id=200)}}">player page</a>
	indicate your skill relative to the rest of the community. Your unadjusted skill is comprised of two key indicators. Mu, the first number, increases and decreases as you win and lose sets.  Sigma, the second number, starts off large and decreases as you play more sets.</p>
	<p class = "left_align">
	The Trueskill number takes your Mu (average approximation of skill) and Sigma (how uncertain we are that your skill lies around that average approximation) and uses Microsoft's suggested ranking formula of  Trueskill = Trueskill Mu - (3 * Trueskill Sigma). You can read more about Trueskill <a href="http://www.moserware.com/2010/03/computing-your-skill.html">here.</a></p>

